Chapter 17. Government as Educator
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \brdrt \brdrcf1 \brdrw20 \brdrs \fs20 \brdrr \brdrcf1 \brdrw0 \brdrs \brdrl \brdrcf1 \brdrw0 \brdrs \ri0 \qj \li0 \brdrb \brdrcf1 \brdrw0 \brdrs 
}
{\b0 \qc \cf20 \f3 \ri0 \i0 \fs24 \li0 
{\b0 \qc \cf20 \f3 \ri0 \i0 \fs24 \li0 
{\b0 \cf20 \f3 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs24 \sa500 \sb600 
\u167\'3f 17:1.60. The Supreme Court\rquote s Rumsfeld v. FAIR decision
\par 
}
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In Rumsfeld v. Forum for Academic and Institutional Rights, Inc.,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb75e6e0279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb75e6e0279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb75e6e0279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
1
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 the Supreme Court, in an 8-0 opinion written by Chief Justice Roberts,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb75e6e1279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb75e6e1279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb75e6e1279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
2
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 rejected the claim of a group of American law schools that the so-called \u8220\'3fSolomon Amendment\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb75e6e2279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb75e6e2279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb75e6e2279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
3
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 was unconstitutional. The Solomon Amendment was enacted by Congress in response to restrictions imposed by law schools on the access of military recruiters to their students because of disagreement with the Government\rquote s \u8220\'3fdon\rquote t ask, don\rquote t tell\u8221\'3f policy on homosexuals in the military. The Forum for Academic and Institutional Rights, Inc., or FAIR, was an association of law schools and law faculties. FAIR members have adopted policies expressing their opposition to discrimination based on, among other factors, sexual orientation. At the time of the Supreme Court\rquote s decision, the Solomon Amendment prevented an institution from receiving certain federal funding if it prohibited military recruiters \u8220\'3ffrom gaining access to campuses, or access to students \u8230\'3f on campuses, for purposes of military recruiting in a manner that is at least equal in quality and scope to the access to campuses and to students that is provided to any other employer.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb760df0279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb760df0279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb760df0279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
4
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The United States Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit held that the Solomon Amendment violated the First Amendment rights of law schools.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb760df1279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb760df1279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb760df1279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
5
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The United States Supreme Court reversed.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb760df2279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb760df2279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb760df2279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
6
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The Supreme Court began its analysis in FAIR by emphasizing the broad powers granted to Congress under the Constitution raise and support armies, provide and maintain a Navy, and provide for the \u8220\'3fcommon Defense.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb760df3279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb760df3279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb760df3279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
7
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Solomon Amendment, the Court held, gives universities a choice: \u8220\'3fEither allow military recruiters the same access to students afforded any other recruiter or forgo certain federal funds.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb760df4279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb760df4279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb760df4279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
8
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 That Congress decided not to regulate the actions of universities directly, but to instead use its spending power, the Court held, did not change the constitutional analysis.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb760df5279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb760df5279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb760df5279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
9
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Court did not deem it necessary to deal with the \u8220\'3fdoctrine of unconstitutional conditions,\u8221\'3f in FAIR, because \u8220\'3fa funding condition cannot be unconstitutional if it could be constitutionally imposed directly.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb760df6279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb760df6279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb760df6279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
10
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 In a sweeping decision, the Court held that \u8220\'3f[b]ecause the First Amendment would not prevent Congress from directly imposing the Solomon Amendment\rquote s access requirement, the statute does not place an unconstitutional condition on the receipt of federal funds.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb760df7279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb760df7279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb760df7279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
11
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The Court in FAIR found dispositive the fundamental fact that the \u8220\'3fSolomon Amendment neither limits what law schools may say nor requires them to say anything.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb763500279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb763500279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb763500279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
12
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Law schools, the Court reasoned, remained free under the statute to express whatever views they may have on the military\rquote s congressionally mandated employment policy, all the while retaining eligibility for federal funds.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb763501279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb763501279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb763501279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
13
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The Court in FAIR held that the principle that the First Amendment prohibits the government from telling people what they must say, established in such landmark cases as West Virginia Board of Education v. Barnette,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb763502279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb763502279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb763502279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
14
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 striking down a law requiring schoolchildren to recite the Pledge of Allegiance and to salute the flag, or Wooley v. Maynard,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb763503279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb763503279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb763503279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
15
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 holding unconstitutional a law that required New Hampshire motorists to display the state motto\u8212\'3f\u8220\'3fLive Free or Die\u8221\'3f\u8212\'3fon their license plates, simply was not implicated in any similarly forceful way. 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
While recruiting assistance provided by the schools often includes elements of speech, such as e-mails or notices on bulletin boards, the Court conceded, this sort of recruiting assistance was nonetheless \u8220\'3fa far cry from the compelled speech in Barnette and Wooley.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb763504279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb763504279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb763504279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
16
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Solomon Amendment, unlike the laws at issue in Barnette or Wooley, did not dictate the content of the speech at all, and was plainly incidental to the Solomon Amendment\rquote s regulation of conduct. The Court noted that \u8220\'3fit has never been deemed an abridgment of freedom of speech or press to make a course of conduct illegal merely because the conduct was in part initiated, evidenced, or carried out by means of language, either spoken, written, or printed\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb763505279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb763505279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb763505279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
17
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 As the Court noted, Congress may prohibit employers from discriminating in hiring on the basis of race. \u8220\'3fThe fact that this will require an employer to take down a sign reading \u8216\'3fWhite Applicants Only\u8217\'3f hardly means that the law should be analyzed as one regulating the employer\rquote s speech rather than conduct.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb763506279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb763506279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb763506279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
18
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Compelling a law school that sends scheduling e-mails for other recruiters to send one for a military recruiter, the Court held, \u8220\'3fis simply not the same as forcing a student to pledge allegiance, or forcing a Jehovah\rquote s Witness to display the motto \u8216\'3fLive Free or Die,\u8217\'3f and it trivializes the freedom protected in Barnette and Wooley to suggest that it is.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb763507279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb763507279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb763507279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
19
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The Supreme Court also held, that the Solomon Amendment did not violate the First Amendment principle that in some circumstances limits the government\rquote s ability to force one speaker to host or accommodate another speaker\rquote s message.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb765c10279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb765c10279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb765c10279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
20
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 In all such prior cases, the Court reasoned, the complaining speaker\rquote s own message was affected by the speech it was forced to accommodate.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb765c11279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb765c11279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb765c11279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
21
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 However, accommodating the military\rquote s message, the Court reasoned, did not affect the law schools\rquote  speech, because the schools are not speaking when they host interviews and recruiting receptions.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb765c12279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb765c12279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb765c12279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
22
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Unlike a parade, the Court held, a law school\rquote s decision to allow recruiters on campus is not inherently expressive.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb765c13279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb765c13279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb765c13279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
23
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 \u8220\'3fA law school\rquote s recruiting services lack the expressive quality of a parade, a newsletter, or the editorial page of a newspaper; its accommodation of a military recruiter\rquote s message is not compelled speech because the accommodation does not sufficiently interfere with any message of the school.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb765c14279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb765c14279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb765c14279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
24
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The Supreme Court rebuffed the claim by law schools that if they treat military and nonmilitary recruiters alike, they could be viewed as sending the message that they see nothing wrong with the military\rquote s policies, when in fact they do. The Court observed that it has rejected a similar argument in PruneYard Shopping Center v. Robins,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb765c15279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb765c15279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb765c15279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
25
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 in which the Court upheld a state law requiring a shopping center owner to allow certain expressive activities by others on its property, holding that there was little likelihood that the views of those engaging in the expressive activities would be identified with the owner, who remained free to disassociate himself from those views and who was not being compelled to affirm a belief in any governmentally prescribed position or view.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb765c16279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb765c16279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb765c16279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
26
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Court found the situation facing law schools under the Solomon Amendment as essentially the equivalent to what happened in PruneYard: \u8220\'3fNothing about recruiting suggests that law schools agree with any speech by recruiters, and nothing in the Solomon Amendment restricts what the law schools may say about the military\rquote s policies.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb765c17279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb765c17279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb765c17279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
27
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Court noted that it had held that high school students can appreciate the difference between speech a school sponsors and speech the school permits because legally required to do so, pursuant to an equal access policy, and that surely law students could make these distinctions as well.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb765c18279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb765c18279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb765c18279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
28
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The Court in FAIR also found unconvincing the claim that the Solomon Amendment impermissibly regulates expressive conduct. The Court noted that it had rejected the view that conduct can be labeled \u8220\'3fspeech\u8221\'3f whenever the person engaging in the conduct intends thereby to express an idea. Rather, First Amendment protection only extends to conduct that is \u8220\'3finherently expressive.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb768320279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb768320279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb768320279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
29
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Court thus contrasted flag-burning, which was held protected in Texas v. Johnson.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb768321279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb768321279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb768321279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
30
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Unlike flag burning, the Court argued, the conduct regulated by the Solomon Amendment was not inherently expressive: \u8220\'3fPrior to the adoption of the Solomon Amendment\rquote s equal-access requirement, law schools expressed their disagreement with the military by treating military recruiters differently from other recruiters. But these actions were expressive only because the law schools accompanied their conduct with speech explaining it.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb768322279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb768322279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb768322279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
31
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Indeed, the Court observed, to the extent that law schools were distancing themselves from military recruiters, even the expressive content of that effort was not overwhelmingly apparent. \u8220\'3fAn observer who sees military recruiters interviewing away from the law school has no way of knowing whether the law school is expressing its disapproval of the military, all the law school\rquote s interview rooms are full, or the military recruiters decided for reasons of their own that they would rather interview someplace else.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb768323279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb768323279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb768323279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
32
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Thus, as the Court saw it, the expressive component of a law school\rquote s rests not in the conduct itself but by the speech that accompanies it.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb768324279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb768324279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb768324279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
33
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Indeed, the Court held, \u8220\'3fthe fact that such explanatory speech is necessary is strong evidence that the conduct at issue here is not so inherently expressive that it warrants protection under O\rquote Brien.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb768325279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb768325279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb768325279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
34
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 If combining speech and conduct were enough to create expressive conduct, the Court observed, \u8220\'3fa regulated party could always transform conduct into \u8216\'3fspeech\u8217\'3f simply by talking about it.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb768326279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb768326279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb768326279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
35
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 As an example, the Court reasoned, \u8220\'3fif an individual announces that he intends to express his disapproval of the Internal Revenue Service by refusing to pay his income taxes, we would have to apply O\rquote Brien to determine whether the Tax Code violates the First Amendment.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb768327279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb768327279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb768327279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
36
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Court held that neither O\rquote Brien nor its progeny supported such a result.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb768328279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb768328279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb768328279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
37
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Even if it were to assume that O\rquote Brien did apply, the Court observed, the Solomon Amendment imposed only an incidental burden on speech that was no greater than is essential, and therefore permissible under O\rquote Brien.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb768329279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb768329279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb768329279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
38
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 \u8220\'3fMilitary recruiting promotes the substantial Government interest in raising and supporting the Armed Forces\u8212\'3fan objective that would be achieved less effectively if the military were forced to recruit on less favorable terms than other employers.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb76aa30279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb76aa30279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb76aa30279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
39
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The issue is not whether other means of raising an army and providing for a navy might be adequate, the Court held. Rather, it suffices that the means chosen by Congress \u8220\'3fadd to the effectiveness of military recruitment.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb76aa31279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb76aa31279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb76aa31279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
40
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The Supreme Court in FAIR also held that the Solomon Amendment does not violate law schools\rquote  right of expressive association, as set forth in cases such as Boy Scouts of America v. Dale,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb76aa32279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb76aa32279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb76aa32279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
41
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 or Roberts v. U.S. Jaycees
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb76aa33279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb76aa33279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb76aa33279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
42
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 \u8220\'3fThe right to speak is often exercised most effectively by combining one\rquote s voice with the voices of others,\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb76aa34279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb76aa34279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb76aa34279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
43
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 the Court observed. \u8220\'3fIf the government were free to restrict individuals\rquote  ability to join together and speak, it could essentially silence views that the First Amendment is intended to protect.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb76aa35279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb76aa35279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb76aa35279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
44
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Court in FAIR contrasted its prior holding in Dale, in which it held that the Boy Scouts\rquote  freedom of expressive association was violated by New Jersey\rquote s public accommodations law, which required the organization to accept a homosexual as a scoutmaster. After determining that the Boy Scouts was an expressive association, the Court in Dale held that \u8220\'3fthe forced inclusion of Dale would significantly affect its expression,\u8221\'3f and that the New Jersey\rquote s interests did not justify this intrusion.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb76aa36279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb76aa36279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb76aa36279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
45
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Solomon Amendment, in contrast, did not, in the Court\rquote s view, similarly affect a law school\rquote s associational rights. It was true that to comply with the statute, law schools must allow military recruiters on campus and assist them in whatever way the school chooses to assist other employers, but recruiters, the Court pointed, out, did not become part of the law school. \u8220\'3fRecruiters are, by definition, outsiders who come onto campus for the limited purpose of trying to hire students\u8212\'3fnot to become members of the school\rquote s expressive association.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb76aa37279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb76aa37279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb76aa37279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
46
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 This distinction, the Court held, is critical. Unlike the public accommodations law in Dale, the Solomon Amendment simply did not force a law school to accept members it did not desire.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb76aa38279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb76aa38279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb76aa38279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
47
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Freedom of expressive association, of course, protects more than just a group\rquote s membership decisions. For example, the Supreme Court had held laws unconstitutional that require disclosure of membership lists for groups seeking anonymity,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb76aa39279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb76aa39279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb76aa39279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
48
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 or laws that imposed penalties or withhold benefits based on membership in a disfavored group.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb76aa3a279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb76aa3a279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb76aa3a279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
49
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Although these laws did not directly interfere with an organization\rquote s composition, the Court observed in FAIR, they made group membership less attractive, raising the same First Amendment concerns about affecting the group\rquote s ability to express its message.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb76d140279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb76d140279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb76d140279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
50
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Yet the Solomon Amendment, the Court held, had no similar effect on a law school\rquote s associational rights. \u8220\'3fStudents and faculty are free to associate to voice their disapproval of the military\rquote s message; nothing about the statute affects the composition of the group by making group membership less desirable.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb76d141279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb76d141279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb76d141279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
51
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 A military recruiter\rquote s mere presence on campus does not violate a law school\rquote s right to associate, regardless of how repugnant the law school considers the recruiter\rquote s message, the Court held.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_Idb76d142279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_Idb76d142279a11f1bc1683b4c14c7e}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_Idb76d142279a11f1bc1683b4c14" }{\fldrslt 
